I started this 30 day yoga challenge in 2017 with my best friend. We were trying to motivate each other to be healthier and more productive. We wanted to improve our lives, we wanted to feel happier! And it was fun to do yoga together! Shortly after we started, my best was killed in a biking accident. The past few years have been really hard for me. I was so unhappy, for so many reasons. About a year ago, I was so tired and so sick, I was addicted to drugs, I wasn't eating or getting out of bed. A couple more big, really tough, things came my way, and then I finally decided I needed a change..So I started to! It has been a slow journey, and 2020 has been hard too, really hard.... but I haven't let myself slip! 26 days ago my mom sent me a link to day 1 of your 30 day yoga challenge, I honestly broke down crying. It was hard to start it again without my friend, but now on day 26 I feel so proud and so happy and I miss her so much but I know she would be proud and happy too. I feel a special connection to these videos and it has made my practice so fulfilling. I appreciate you, Adriene so much, you are such a bright soul! beaming! You have helped me a lot. Omg I am here 8/7/2020 and  my life has changed thanks to Adriene! My breathing, my attitude, my energy. I feel like a new person. Physically, emotionally, mentally..

Those tabletop crunches were not easy haha. I really enjoyed all the stretching and breathing with this practice though. It made the time go by really fast and I was surprised when we got into Shavasana. I feel like I've been having a hard time with motivation for the last week almost and my daily workouts have become a lot more of a chore than they used to be. I really hope I get my second wind soon because I don't want to quit, I want to keep up this habit because honestly, it's the best thing I've done for myself in years. I almost feel like I've hit a wall and that's why I'm losing motivation. When I first started I was improving practically every day, but as I continue to practice I have slowed down in my progress and sometimes I feel like I'm even doing worse. I realize this is natural and it happens to everybody. Progress isn't exponential and I won't be seeing obvious improvement in such a short amount of time. Knowing that doesn't make it any less discouraging though. I also realize this is a temporary mood and that if I just keep myself mentally strong and push past this apathetic wall that I will start to enjoy myself again. These 26 days with Adriene have been a complete joy, however, and leaving these daily comments have been very therapeutic, almost like a diary haha. It really helps me to check in with myself and recognize how I feel both mentally and physically.

I'm not here looking for pity. But my mum, my most important person is suffering but I can't help her. Regardless of what me or her family is telling her she chose to stay blind. She's in a toxic relationship. But because the guy doesn't beat her, she think it's okay. Because the guy bought her a home, then it's okay. She's married to him. I've tried everything but now I'm tired and decided to not talk to her. But it hurts and it's so difficult. So difficult to not respond to her msg but everytime I get into a fight with the guy, next day she act as if nothing happened. I can't keep on pretending like this. So difficult to go on my life, be in my happy relationship why she suffers. It's horrible. I don't get why she won't wake up. My mum has always been strong but she became so fragile, skittish. The guy always belittle her... I get into fight with him as my mum confide in me but I can't stand by without not doing anything. 

So regardless of that today I got on my mat. I didn't smile while stretching, all I could do was cry. But I'm still thankful to have this video.

This might be too honest, but as a person who struggles with disordered eating, this is doing wonders for me. I usually think of exercise exclusively as a means to expand calories. But when I get on the mat, I forget about that. Instead of constantly thinking "Now I've burnt x many calories", I feel like I can fully inhabit and feel my body and its movements for a little while without my mind getting in the way. 

I used to give up on exercise when things got hard, because I could only focus on how I wished I looked and that's frankly not a very good motivation. Just makes you feel bad. (SO BAD). But this doesn't feel that way at all; it feels fun and playful, even when it's challenging. Has pretty much changed my entire relationship with exercise, and helps relieve so much stress.

I like the restorative practices that teach us to take care of our temple. Coming from an army background, we were taught that “pain is weakness leaving the body!”.... No. If the body is in pain, it’s a sign to slow down to restore. Just the other day I injured my knee working out. I totally babied that knee and I’m back at it with functioning knees. You don’t have to “push through” everything, and that’s why I love restorative yoga because it reminds you to love your body, and not force it. Yoga in general does this, but restorative yoga specifically highlights this point. 🧘🏾‍♀️ Namaste 🙏🏾

I started yoga with Adrienne about 3 months ago. I have been struggling with a number of complicated issues. Type 1 diabetes, fibromyalgia and gastroparesis (a complication of stomach neuropathy due to labile diabetes - simplified explanation.)

We all have issues of one kind or another, struggles that limit us. Adrienne you have given us the freedom to fly when we are held grounded by our ailments both physical and mental. Your experience, your advice are just beautiful gems of wisdom. Your approach is so generous and inviting. I  researched yoga before I started. I swear I found you, (although millions had found you first), you embody such grace and warmth; it is felt through the screen. 

Through you, I have found some peace, and pleasure for the first time in a long time. I must live on a very restricted and limited diet just to not feel sick. Food is everything to me, it is how I show my love, it is family and friends. Now it is the enemy that stops me from experiencing those pleasures; this basic pleasure. You and the gift you have given us has become as needed and as basic as simply eating yummy food again.  Thank you for helping me find a place in my world again.
